5
00:00:23,620 --> 00:00:32,600
Now we'll test it and see at what frequencies we always work, and what frequencies are actually needed.

6
00:00:33,380 --> 00:00:45,020
For this we need this auxiliary instrument, ferrite ring mark 1500-2000, can be higher, doesn't matter.

7
00:00:45,360 --> 00:00:50,700
Wind 8-10 turns, resistance not needed, we don't track exact phasing.

8
00:00:51,460 --> 00:00:59,460
We just need to know current amplitude in this system.

9
00:01:00,160 --> 00:01:01,800
Meaning of how this works.

10
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:17,360
When electric current moves through a conductor, or charges are in place but spin rotation happens, around the conductor magnetic field forms.

11
00:01:17,360 --> 00:01:30,300
When this ring is put on, magnetic field is captured and on these turns converts it to voltage potential, which we track on oscilloscope.

12
00:01:31,260 --> 00:01:48,660
To track current movement in this coil, we'll need coil leads, short between each other physically, galvanically, and already see when this coil works on half-wave.

13
00:01:50,620 --> 00:01:51,880
Where do we start?

14
00:01:52,940 --> 00:01:56,780
Put ring on any of leads, short,

15
00:01:59,870 --> 00:02:05,110
make good contact and connect oscilloscope.

16
00:02:07,370 --> 00:02:08,870
Phasing isn't important.

17
00:02:12,360 --> 00:02:14,620
Common and probe itself.

18
00:02:16,220 --> 00:02:22,880
